<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Serbia opens up Bosnian camps: Women and children allowed to
leave Sarajevo Aid convoys given better access
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BANJA LUKA, NORTH-WEST BOSNIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBIA yesterday bowed to international pressure by opening up some
detention camps in Bosnia-Hercegovina and by allowing greater access to some
towns and cities in the former Yugoslav republic for humanitarian relief
supplies.
The Serbs also agreed to let mothers and children begin leaving the Bosnian
capital of Sarajevo, which Serb irregular forces have been besieging for
four months. The first convoy of buses with 300 women and children is due to
leave today with an escort of United Nations peacekeepers.
Ms Sylvana Foa, an official with the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR), said aid convoys for Bosnia were now getting through more
quickly and easily. 'Once these people have realised how outraged the world
community would be by the sight of people starving to death, that had a
major impact, probably more than even the threat of the use of force,' she
added.
But the Serb move to lessen their grip on some areas is also aimed at
pre-empting any international military intervention, threatened in a UN
draft resolution expected to be put to the Security Council today.
It also indicates a growing confidence on the part of Serb leaders that
their forces have achieved most of their aims in Bosnia. Mr Radovan
Karadzic, head of Bosnia's Serbs, said yesterday his forces had already
achieved their aims, implying that he was now in a position to co-operate
fully with the UN.
'We have everything. We now control 70 per cent (of the territory of Bosnia)
but we only claim 64 per cent. All we need now is a negotiated settlement,'
he said in an interview.
A spokesman for the UNHCR warned that Serbs were still expelling Bosnia's
Moslems, who make up 43 per cent of the 4.3m-strong population. The official
said that about 20,000 Moslems would be forcibly deported from the region
around Bihac, north-western Bosnia, to neighbouring Croatia as part of Mr
Karadzic's plan for 'ethnic cleansing' of those parts of Bosnia under Serb
control.
The agreement to evacuate mothers and children from Sarajevo was reached by
Serb forces and a children's aid organisation. Some of the first evacuees
will go to Austria and others to Croatia.
The UN draft resolution calls on all states to take 'all measures necessary
to facilitate, in co-ordination with the UN, the delivery of humanitarian
assistance to Sarajevo, and wherever needed in other parts of
Bosnia-Hercegovina'. The resolution also demands unimpeded and continuous
access to all camps, prisons and detention centres.
UN diplomats said they expected support from most Security Council members,
although Russia, a traditional ally of Serbia, showed signs of distancing
itself from supporting UN sanctions imposed on Belgrade last May. It also
refrained from condemning the existence of detention camps.
In London, Mr Thomas Niles, US assistant secretary of state for European and
Canadian affairs, said he hoped the adoption of the resolution 'will make it
possible to (deliver aid) peacefully and without any use of military force'.
But he said 'military measures would be contemplated . . . as a last
resort'.
Nato is likely to discuss this issue on Friday when all 16 member states
meet to consider contingency plans for the possible use of force in Bosnia.
Serbs scent victory in war-torn Bosnia, Page 2
Concentration camps a myth, say Russians, Page 2
</TEXT>
