<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Building societies hold rates despite increase by Skipton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE building societies yester-day moved to head off a general increase in
mortgage interest rates after Skipton, the 14th largest society, raised its
rates for investors and borrowers.
Skipton, which has assets of Pounds 2.7bn, triggered fears of a general rise
in mortgages when it announced that the rate it charges existing borrowers
would rise by 0.5 of a percentage point to 11.25 per cent from today. New
customers will be charged 10.99 per cent.
Alliance &amp; Leicester and National &amp; Provincial, the two large building
societies which were thought most likely to follow Skipton, made it clear
that they would not do so, reducing the immediate likelihood of a general
rise.
Alliance, the fourth largest society, said it did not wish to do anything
that might depress the housing market still further and so would be very
reluctant to raise its mortgage rate.
Mr David O'Brien, chief executive of National &amp; Provincial, the sixth
largest, said: 'We believe building societies should continue to encourage
confidence in house-buying through attractive mortgages.'
The forbearance may be only temporary, according to Mr John Wriglesworth,
building society analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, the stockbroker. 'I think
because of the pressures on societies, mortgage rates may rise gradually
over the remainder of 1992, but they will do so in a ragged fashion as
lenders withdraw special offers and discounts,' he said.
Instead of raising their mortgage rates immediately, the large societies may
cut their rates for savers, after two similar moves earlier this month by
National Savings, which trimmed its rates to relieve pressure on the
societies.
Bradford &amp; Bingley, the seventh largest society, yesterday said it was
cutting its rates to savers by 0.45 of a percentage point from August 15.
Nationwide, the second largest, made a similar move last week.
Mr Geoffrey Lister, Bradford &amp; Bingley's chief executive, said the society
had decided to reduce its rates because of the fall in the inflation rate
rather than widen its margins by increasing its mortgage rates.
These moves will pose difficulties for smaller societies, which are thought
to have been especially hard hit recently by savers' reluctance to place
their money with building societies.
The larger societies, however, may find it difficult to hold down their
savings rates for the rest of the year. Several are already close to the
ceiling on the amount they are allowed to raise in the wholesale money
market.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
