<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE battle over ownership of LTV's aircraft and missiles businesses
continued to escalate yesterday, when LTV announced it had a new offer of
Dollars 475m from the Loral/Carlyle/Northrop team.
Only a week ago, LTV announced a preliminary agreement to sell its entire
aircraft and missiles operations to defence group Martin Marietta for
Dollars 440m. This came only days after defence group Loral offered Dollars
240m for LTV's missiles business, in a joint bid with the Carlyle Group, a
Washington investment firm, and defence company Northrop, which together
offered Dollars 190m for LTV's aircraft side.
The latest offer consists of Dollars 450m in cash and Dollars 25m in
referred stock. The bidding partners said it exceeded the Martin Marietta
offer by Dollars 35m, and by Dollars 54m in cash. They also said that
Carlyle and Northrop had already received Hart-Scott-Rodino clearance, and
that Loral's closing was not conditional on Hart-Scott-Rodino clearance.
The deal still needs approval of the bankruptcy court, which oversees LTV's
assets.
