<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Producer price rises slow to 1968 rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRICES of manufactured goods leaving Britain's factories rose in the
year to July at the lowest annual rate since 1968.
A 0.1 per cent rise in the producer prices index last month brought the
year-on-year increase to 3.4 per cent compared with 3.5 per cent in June.
The index, often taken as a measure of core inflation, has fallen from a
peak of 6.2 per cent in April 1991 to July's 3.4 per cent, responding to
government attempts to squeeze the upward pressure on prices and reflecting
weak domestic demand.
Further evidence of the disinflationary momentum in the economy comes from
the rise in the index once volatile food, drink and tobacco prices are
excluded. This increased by 0.1 per cent on the month, bringing the
year-on-year rise to 2.8 per cent compared with 2.9 per cent in the year to
June.
The seasonally-adjusted prices of raw materials and fuels used by
manufacturing industry were flat in July compared with the previous month,
but remained 1.5 per cent down on a year ago.
Input prices unadjusted for seasonal factors fell by 0.7 per cent last month
compared with June, reflecting depressed commodity prices. The Treasury said
falling input prices with stable unit-labour costs would ensure further
reductions in the annual rate of producer price inflation over the coming
months.
On Friday, the retail prices index for July is expected to show a small rise
from June's 3.9 per cent before resuming a downward path later this year.
Factory gate prices, Page 6
</TEXT>
