<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Bowater told to sell offshoot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, acted yesterday to
prevent concentration of power in the medical bags and pouches market.
He has asked the Bowater packaging group to dispose of one of its two
businesses in the sector, under threat of a referral to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission. Bowater built up a dominant position in the market after
acquiring DRG Packaging in March.
Mr David Jones, Bowater's finance director, accepted that its two businesses
had a combined share of 51 per cent of an Pounds 11m market. He added that
Bowater had not anticipated competition problems.
Bowater can sell either its Welton bags and pouches business, which has
annual sales of about Pounds 2m, or the medical bags subsidiary of the DRG
group, with a turnover of Pounds 4m. 'Either way, we will still have a
significant share of the market,' Mr Jones said.
The company's shares fell on the news but recovered to close 5p lower at
734p on the day after Bowater disclosed that the action affected a business
that accounted for less than 2 per cent of DRG's turnover.
</TEXT>
