<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Cadbury proposals too vague, accountants say
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CODE on corporate governance proposed by the Cadbury committee is too
vague to be effective, the Chartered Association of Certified Accountants
said yesterday.
The association, which represents 38,000 accountants, said in its response
to the proposals that annual reports should give a statement of principles,
setting out goals and how effectively they have been met.
It said the objectives set by Cadbury required far more clearly defined
responsibilities and methods of compliance by bodies including the Stock
Exchange and the Financial Reporting Council.
The association called for more weight to be given to internal audit and
control systems and for less reliance on non-executive directors. It said
the guidelines should be extended to smaller companies.
Separately, Arthur Andersen, the accountancy firm, issued a submission
arguing that the Cadbury committee should be more forthright on the
supervisory role taken by company boards.
It said responsibilities should be allocated to specific non-executive
directors, and consideration given to creating 'two-tier' boards in which
non-executives would act as guardians of shareholders' interests,
scrutinising the work of executive directors.
It also called for interim and annual financial statements to be published
more quickly - perhaps three months after the period in question.
The committee, which issued its draft proposals in May, is to produce a
final report in November.
</TEXT>
