<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Telephone charges set to fall as BT agrees toOftel plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TELEPHONE charges are set to fall after BT yesterday accepted a stricter
pricing regime.
BT agreed to implement proposals by Oftel, the telecommunications regulator,
by keeping price changes on a range of services to 7.5 percentage points
below the rate of inflation.
At present, price changes have to be kept to 6.25 per cent below inflation -
as measured by the retail prices index.
The new pricing regime, which will last for four years starting next August,
means that BT's 19m residential and 6.5m business customers can expect real
cuts in charges while inflation, currently about 4 per cent, stays below 7.5
per cent.
One immediate benefit for consumers is that connection charges are set to
come down by 40 per cent from Pounds 163.75 to Pounds 99.
The agreement between BT and Oftel follows two months of heated negotiations
during which relations between the two became increasingly strained.
The City welcomed the decision by BT, whose shares closed up 1p at 333p. The
agreement will lead to lower revenues, but the threat of being referred to
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission was removed.
According to Mr Peter Golob at SG Warburg Securities, this was 'a far
greater threat than anything else'.
While BT decided to accept all Oftel's main proposals, it said it had
seriously considered rejecting them - a move which would have triggered a
reference to the commission. This option was ruled out due to the
uncertainty for the business and demands on senior management time.
BT's decision contrasts with that of British Gas, which recently chose to go
to the commission rather than agree to stricter price controls proposed by
its regulator.
However, BT criticised Oftel's tough stance, saying that its proposals
represented 'a significant change in direction towards more interventionist
regulation, which could impede the development of the truly competitive and
open marketplace that everyone is aiming for'.
The deal, which comes at a time when BT's profit growth is expected to come
largely from cost cutting rather than additional revenue, puts more pressure
on the group to reduce costs. It has already announced plans to cut 35,000
jobs this year, and a further 15,000 each year over the next two to three
years.
New telecoms licences, Page 7
Lex, Page 18
