<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Central banks step in to halt dollar's decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONCERTED intervention by the world's leading central banks yesterday halted
the dollar's decline but failed to give the US currency much of a lift.
As many as 15 central banks bought dollars for D-Marks in what appeared to
be a determined effort to establish a floor for the US currency.
Mr Johann Wilhelm Gaddum, a member of the Bundesbank's policymaking central
council, said in Frankfurt that the buying was initiated by the US Federal
Reserve. The intervention began as the dollar was falling towards DM1.461 in
quiet lunchtime trading in Europe and continued during the afternoon.
Analysts thought the central banks, which included the Bundesbank, the Bank
of England and the central banks of France, Switzerland, Italy, Canada and
Spain, bought more than Dollars 500m altogether. The intervention, however,
was less effective than the most recent bout of concerted official support
on July 20 when a similar number of central banks bought Dollars 400m at
about DM1.447.
Yesterday's action pushed the dollar up quickly by about 1 1/2 pfennigs, but
it later slipped back to stand at DM1.4670 in late New York trading, while
in Tokyo early today it opened at DM1.46575. July's intervention lifted the
dollar by 5 pfennigs.
A US Treasury Department official said the action was a sign that the US and
other members of the Group of Seven industrial countries did not wish the
dollar to depreciate. But statements by other policymakers gave less support
to the US currency.
The dollar softened after Mr Gaddum said there was no firm dollar exchange
rate that the Bundesbank would commit itself to defend through intervention.
Mr Nicholas Brady, US treasury secretary, was quoted by news agencies as
telling a political gathering at Scottsdale, Arizona, that the US did not
have a policy to cheapen the dollar. But any support provided by this remark
was offset by Mr Brady's later statement that there was 'no reason why (US)
interest rates shouldn't be lower'.
Analysts speculated that the Fed intervened to prop up the dollar for fear
it could start a free fall if it dropped through its previous record low of
DM1.443, set in February 1991. There are few signs of inflationary pressure
in the US but such a decline could harbour risks for the future.
Of more pressing concern could be the fragile state of world equity markets.
In the past week, Wall Street has fallen, while Tokyo's 225-share Nikkei
average has dropped to levels last seen in early 1986. Yesterday, it closed
at 14,822,56, down 243.78. This morning share prices edged higher, with the
Nikkei up some 50 points in initial trading.
The intervention boosted European equities. German shares rose in
after-market dealings, while in London, the FT-SE 100 index closed at
2,309.6, down 16.1, but well up on the day's low. In New York the Dow Jones
Industrial Average was down 6.48 at 3,331.10.
Tokyo share values at six-year low, Page 3
