<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / International Company News: Intl Paper pays Dollars 120m for
stake in Polish unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Paper, the US forest products group, yesterday announced its
first venture in eastern Europe with the acquisition of an 80 per cent stake
in Poland's second biggest paper manufacturer.
International Paper will pay Dollars 120m for its stake in Kwidzyn Pulp and
Paper Company. It will also invest another Dollars 175m over the next four
years as part of a programme to modernise and expand the company.
The deal was announced by Mr Janusz Lewandowski, Poland's minister of
privatisation.
Kwidzyn, which started production in the early 1980s, recorded sales of
930bn zlotys (Dollars 71.5m) in the first five months of this year and
pre-tax profits of 45bn zlotys. It is Poland's only integrated bleached pulp
and paper company.
The move comes when International Paper has started to look further afield
for acquisitions, after expanding aggressively in the US and western Europe
in the 1980s. About Dollars 4bn of the company's roughly Dollars 13bn in
annual sales comes from western European operations.
International Paper has agreed not to make any Kwidzyn employees redundant
within the next 18 months and to maintain existing social benefits. In the
US, International Paper ran into trouble with its unions in 1987 over
proposed cuts in wages and benefits which resulted in a lock-out at one mill
and a 16-month strike at three others.
Mr George Adler, an analyst at Smith Barney Harris Upham in New York
described the investment as 'very interesting. This seems to be a fairly
modern mill - the first machine was put in there in 1985'.
</TEXT>
