<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / London Stock Exchange: Wellcome 'floor' lowered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FLOOR set on the Wellcome share price at the recent share issue began to
suffer yesterday from wet rot seeping in from the rest of the stock market.
Because of the general fall in market, the floor was lowered from 800p to
780p and shares in the pharmaceuticals group fell 18 1/2 to 782p with 7.7m
traded.
Wellcome Trust, the charity which has been reducing its majority
shareholding, had said it would buy up to 40m shares until the issue closes.
This 'green shoe' buy-back option allows the issue price to be stabilised.
Robert Fleming, lead broker for the global sale, had announced that it would
support a price of 800p. However, some analysts pointed out that, in this
case, selling Wellcome shares provided a guaranteed exit from a falling
stock market.
On Monday, two large institutions offloaded large lines of stock. As a
result, Fleming told Morgan Stanley, the lead US broker, to quote Wellcome
at a market level in New York, where the shares are traded in the form of
American Depositary Receipts (ADRs). The ADRs were quoted overnight around
Dollars 15, the equivalent of 782p.
When London opened, Fleming followed suit, cutting its bid price, and
arguing that the new level reflected the general fall in the market since
the strike price was set on July 27. Fleming is believed to have bought
about half of the green shoe allocation so far. The final closing date for
the issue is August 26.
BA declines
Disappointment at a fall in British Airways' (BA) passenger yield in the
three months to June 30 saw a fall in the shares after first quarter results
just shy of market forecasts.
By the close the shares had given up 8 to 253p in average trade of 4.4m
shares. Profits for the period April to June reached Pounds 91m, against
Pounds 9m in the same period last year. tA good result had been anticipated
from the UK's leading airliner which led to strong demand for the stock
ahead of the results, however a close examination of the figures left the
market slightly disappointed with the underlying profits figure.
Nonetheless, Mr Chris Will at Lehman Brothers remained positive on the stock
and said he was maintaining his full year profits forecast at Pounds 400m
because, 'the falls in the yield have been more than matched by the cuts in
costs'.
Waters easier
Water shares were generally weaker amid investor concern about tomorrow's
Ofwat report on quality standards in the industry. Recommendations are
expected on issues including metering, leakage, and capital expenditure.
Detailed costings are unlikely, however, as three other reports due in
coming weeks address the sector's cost base more closely.
Analysts said yesterday that the outlook for the sector remained positive
and that fears had been exaggerated. Mr Stephen Doe at Smith New Court said:
'The regulatory nervousness has been overdone. Higher capital spending will
prolong growth in the sector.' Among the main movers yesterday, Thames lost
12 to 385p, Welsh 10 to 413p and Yorkshire 13 to 410p.
Insurer General Accident was one of the strongest performers in the FT-SE
100 index as half-year results beat most expectations. The shares were up 13
at best and closed 8 higher at 398p.
The firm posted a half-year loss of Pounds 21.2m against a loss of Pounds
105.2m previously. Analysts' forecasts ranged from a loss of Pounds 20m to
Pounds 52m. The group said UK underwriting losses had improved as action on
premiums and cost controls took effect, helping the company to make a profit
in the second quarter.
Banks were generally stronger but a couple were put under pressure by
downgrades. Barclays fell 4 to 300p after a sell recommendation issued by
Carr Kitcat &amp; Aitken. Analyst Mr Derek Chambers cut his forecast for this
year's profits to Pounds 300m from Pounds 450m and for 1993 to around Pounds
450m from Pounds 1bn, the latter believed to be around the bottom of the
range of analysts forecasts.
Bank of Scotland lost 2 to 100p in early trade after Credit Lyonnais Laing
cut its current year profit forecast for the group to Pounds 135m from
Pounds 177.5m previously. The bank made Pounds 140m in the year to the end
of February. The cut was prompted by a downward revision in net interest
income.
Hongkong and Shanghai Bank saw heavy turnover of 10m shares as a block of 5m
was traded at 328p. The shares were unchanged at 328p.
Speculation later denied that James Capel had changed its attitude to RTZ
prompted the world's biggest mining group to close 25 lower at 525p.
Oils were firm as investors speculated on renewed tension in the Middle
East. Among the gainers BP lifted 2 to 189 1/2 p with 22m shares traded and
Enterprise rose 7 to 347p.
Switching out of Guinness and into Grand Metropolitan continued. Guinness
shares dropped 12 to 516p, Grand Met lifted 9 to 425p. Allied-Lyons, another
Kleinwort buy, added 4 to 602p.
BZW's review of the food manufacturing sector continued on the back of what
it considers tough trading conditions. Yesterday, the house trimmed
forecasts for Associated British Foods by Pounds 10m to Pounds 305m for this
year, and United Biscuits, by Pounds 5m to Pounds 195m. AB Foods shed 7 to
386p, while UB tumbled 12 to 300p. A James Capel downgrade was said to have
unhinged Northern Foods, off 11 at 232p.
Ranks Hovis McDougall slipped 4 to 168p as a block of 4.6m shares went
through the market at 150p, taking turnover to a hefty 5.6m,
Textile group Coats Viyella saw unusually heavy turnover as one institution
sold 3.8m shares at 161 1/2 p through Smith New Court which placed the
shares at 162p. The shares closed 6 lower at 165p with recorded turnover of
8.7m.
A squeeze continued in BAA and the shares gained 4 to 629p. Rolls-Royce
eased a penny to 138p.
MARKET REPORTERS:
Peter John,
Joel Kibazo.
Christopher Price
Other market statistics,
