<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Liverpool backs Tory homes plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TENANTS of 67 council-owned tower blocks in Liverpool voted overwhelmingly
yesterday for their homes to be transferred to independent management under
a Housing Action Trust (HAT) for a Pounds 100m-plus improvement programme.
The vote represents a breakthrough for government plans to reform
local-authority housing. Two other projects have been agreed - but the one
in Liverpool is the biggest so far in terms of homes affected.
HATs, introduced in 1988, were slow to get off the ground. Several proposals
were rejected in ballots of tenants. Tenants' fears have been allayed by
concessions, including the right to return to local-authority control after
the completion of improvements.
A significant factor in yesterday's 82 per cent vote for the Liverpool HAT
was the support of Mr Harry Rimmer, Labour leader of Liverpool City Council
 -Labour councils have generally been hostile to HATs, fearing loss of
control.
Mr Rimmer said yesterday: 'It is a departure from what had become
established thinking by Labour authorities. But we could not afford to
improve people's quality of life without trying something different. We just
did not have enough resources to afford it.'
The vote allows more than Pounds 100m of government funds to be spent on the
67 blocks over the next 10 years. Only four of the city's 71 blocks voted to
stay with the council, which will be responsible for funding any
refurbishment and improvements.
The new HAT will cover 5,700 homes. The other HATs are a Pounds 55m,
2,100-home programme in Hull and a Pounds 170m, 2,837-home programme
covering four council estates in Waltham Forest, London. Several
Labour-controlled London boroughs are now expected to ballot tenants on
HATs.
The government says HATs are a means of targeting spending, rather than
putting it into a pool. After the HAT programme is completed, tenants are
asked to choose who they want their landlord to be. They can opt to return
to local-authority control if they wish, or choose a housing association or
private landlord.
The Liverpool HAT will cover only 8 per cent of the city's council housing
stock of 60,000 homes, 40,000 of which are officially rated as sub-standard.
In the ballot, conducted by the Electoral Reform Society, turnout was 78.7
per cent.
</TEXT>
