<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 92 / Limit set on insolvency probes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSOLVENCY practitioners need not mount detailed investigations into the
conduct of directors of insolvent companies, according to guidance from
their professional bodies.
An advisory note, issued yesterday, provides guidance on the D-forms, or
statutory reports, that must be submitted to the directors' disqualification
unit of the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) after each insolvency.
It appears to place little responsibility on insolvency practitioners to be
satisfied with directors' conduct of a business.
The guidance, from the Society for the Practitioners of Insolvency and the
Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales, says practitioners
should base their reports on information gained in the ordinary course of
their work.
It suggests that practitioners 'may find it useful' to issue questionnaires
to directors asking for information and 'inviting comments' on the reasons
for an insolvency. It cautions against defamation and says the report to the
DTI, to be submitted within six months of an insolvency appointment, should
be based on proper evidence.
Insolvency guidance notes 3.1008-3.1010. ICAEW, Gloucester House, 399
Silbury Blvd, Central Milton Keynes MK9 2HL. Free with SAE.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
