<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / Ministers form spending body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, are to be members of the government's public expenditure
committee, announced last month.
The other members are Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, who will serve as
chairman; Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury; Mr William
Waldegrave, public service and science minister, and Mr Tony Newton and Lord
Wakeham, leaders respectively of the Commons and the Lords.
The committee, which meets for the first time next month, will seek to
ensure that the government sticks to its planning total for public
expenditure by arbitrating on individual departmental bids.
The body will submit a list of options for meeting the planning total to the
cabinet, which will decide departmental allocations. The regime is intended
to demonstrate the extent of government determination to limit increases in
the public-sector borrowing requirement by linking spending to the expected
low economic growth in the next few years.
Downing Street said yesterday that Mr Clarke and Mr Heseltine had been
appointed in their capacity as spending ministers. Since some committee
decisions might have implications for legislation it was sensible to have
two ministers involved who handled legislative matters.
</TEXT>
