   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ERNST &amp; YOUNG, the ac-countancy firm, is to pay up to Pounds 1.44m in
compensation to shareholders in Sound Diffusion, the failed electrical
equipment manufacturer to which it was auditor and adviser.
The firm has agreed to offer all shareholders in Sound Diffusion 25 per cent
of the value of rights exercised in a Pounds 9.94m rights issue in May 1988,
seven months before the company went into receivership.
Mr David Wilson, national marketing partner at Ernst &amp; Young, emphasised
yesterday that the firm did not accept any liability, but felt it had a
'moral responsibility' to offer the same terms as those agreed with one
shareholder in a legal action concluded last month. In early July it agreed
to pay Pounds 1.35m to Tunstall Group, the security and communications
equipment supplier, which bought Pounds 1.7m of Sound Diffusion shares in
the rights issue.
Mr Wilson said shareholders should contact Ernst &amp; Young's solicitors,
McKenna &amp; Co to make their claims.
Arthur Young took over as auditor to Sound Diffusion from Ernst &amp; Whinney in
1987. The two firms merged in 1989 to become Ernst &amp; Young.
A Department of Trade &amp; Industry inquiry into Sound Diffusion said: 'Arthur
Young either failed to identify or otherwise accepted serious defects in the
company's lease accounting practices and did not adequately audit the amount
receivable under finance leases.'
