FT  11 AUG 92 / Action demanded over sea pollution
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GREENPEACE, the environmental pressure group, yesterday accused the
government of allowing companies to make the UK the worst sea polluter in
western Europe.
It said government data showed that 5,046 tonnes of toxic waste a year was
going into the seas.
It also claimed that a report from the National Rivers Authority (NRA) would
show that this has led to seas off the rivers Thames, Humber, Tees, Tyne,
Wyre, Mersey, Dee, Severn and Solent becoming pollution 'hot spots'.
Mr Tim Birch, Greenpeace toxics campaigner, said: 'The public need to know
the government and NRA are allowing British industry to destroy our rivers
and seas.'
Greenpeace is calling on the government to set clear timetables for the
phasing out of toxic discharges. Its ship Solo is to tour the most polluted
areas, starting with visits to the Wash and the Humber tomorrow.
The campaign is aimed at drawing attention to the problem before western
European environment ministers meet in Paris next month to agree a new
convention to protect seas into the next century.
