<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / Chinese investors take to the streets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SHENZHEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TENS of thousands of stock speculators yesterday rampaged through China's
southern city of Shenzhen to denounce alleged corruption over share
allocations, witnesses said, Reuter reports from Shenzhen.
In some of the worst violence to hit China's brief but turbulent flirtation
with stock market capitalism, protestors chanting 'down with corruption'
kicked and beat plain-clothes police, set a van ablaze and overturned
several vehicles.
Near-hysteria has gripped the industrial city, which borders Hong Kong,
since up to a million potential capitalists invaded Shenzhen at the weekend
trying to buy share application forms.
Egged on by official media reports of ordinary Chinese making fortunes in
stock trading, vast numbers of investors have tried to cash in on both
soaring markets.
Allegations in Shenzhen of official corruption abounded. 'We're angry,' said
one protestor. 'Police used their power to get their relatives into the best
places in the queues.'
Riot police fired at least 10 teargas shells in one part of the city, which
is a showcase for China's reform drive, to try to control the crowd.
In another area few police were visible and demonstrators chased off a group
of about 10 officers watching helplessly from the edge of seeking a highway.
Shenzhen, a booming city at the forefront of China's drive to modernise, has
come to symbolise the economic reforms of Deng Xiaopeng, the senior leader.
But the sale of forms, which entitled investors to apply for shares to be
issued on the Shenzhen stock market in the 1992-93 financial year,
degenerated into turmoil at the weekend.
Police reported one person was crushed to death in Sunday's mayhem, although
the authorities later denied anyone had been killed or seriously injured in
the stampede for forms.
Thousands of investors failed to get any forms, even though 5m were
officially on sale and by yesterday evening trouble had begun. Police
shouted over loud-hailers that more forms would go on sale today but few
demonstrators believed them.
At least six vehicles were overturned including a police car while
protestors set a van on fire.
China's two stock markets in Shanghai and Shenzhen have had a turbulent
history since they reopened officially in 1990 and last year respectively
under China's free-market reforms.
Shanghai trading has been marked by several stampedes, while two men were
murdered earlier this year in Shenzhen as gangsters fought over positions in
queues of share buyers. Shenzhen authorities later launched a series of
swoops to arrest hundreds of gangsters in the special economic zone.
Analysts say it is vital for the authorities to restore order on the
markets. With backing from Deng Xiaoping, the senior leader who visited
Shenzhen early this year, stock markets have flourished in recent months and
prices have soared.
The analysts also say any such disorder gives hardline conservatives in the
leadership ammunition in their fight against reform and they note even Deng
said the markets should be closed down if they proved a failure.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
