<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / Sharp fall in demand for credit as consumers repay more
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND for credit fell sharply in June as consumers paid back more than they
borrowed on credit agreements excluding mortgages.
The news, indicating that consumers are reluctant to spend, came as the
latest consensus of forecasts from the City and economic think tanks shows
output falling by 0.5 per cent this year.
Forecasters have revised expectations for growth sharply downwards since the
middle of the year when it became clear that a post-election surge in
confidence had not turned into sustainable growth. This week a string of
indicators is expected to show that the economy remains stuck in recession
although inflation continues to fall.
In June consumers repaid a net Pounds 55m on credit agreements with finance
houses, building societies and bank credit cards that are part of the Visa
or Mastercard system. This compares with net borrowing of Pounds 68m in May.
According to the new series of figures from the Central Statistical Office,
this was the first time since December that consumers paid back more than
they borrowed. In the first five months of the year they borrowed but more
slowly than in the equivalent period a year ago. The previous CSO credit
business series distorted the net lending figure downwards by treating debts
written off by banks as repayments.
Consumers were wrongly believed to have been making the repayment of debts a
priority in five of the first six months of the year. In fact, they added to
their debts in every month except June.
The seasonally adjusted figures, which do not include mortgages and account
for about 15 per cent of total private-sector debt, showed that demand for
credit shrank in the second quarter compared with the first quarter. Net
lending grew by only Pounds 39m in the three months to June compared with
Pounds 120m in the previous three months.
The amount of new credit advanced in June was Pounds 4.2bn compared with
Pounds 3.8bn in May. It grew by 1.7 per cent in the second quarter compared
with the previous quarter.
A broader measure of net lending to consumers, including bank overdrafts and
loans from insurance companies and retailers, shows that consumers borrowed
a net Pounds 54m in the second quarter compared with Pounds 93m in the first
quarter.
