<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / West drafts UN plan for use of force in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, JUDY DEMPSEY and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE UN, NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN last night reached agreement with the US and France on a draft
United Nations resolution calling for the use of force, if needed, to
deliver humanitarian aid in the former Yugoslav republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina.
The draft resolution also endorses international demands for access to
Serb-controlled detention camps. Concern about the camps and human rights
abuses in the former Yugoslavia is spelt out further in a separate draft
resolution.
The two draft texts, also agreed by Belgium, were submitted last night to
the other members of the 15-nation Security Council in closed-door
consultations at the UN in New York. They are not expected to come to a vote
until tomorrow or Thursday.
The proposals were hammered out after days of negotiations to bypass
differences between western powers about the scope of any military
involvement in the former Yugoslavia. Pressure for some kind of gesture has
grown with media reports of Serb detention camps holding emaciated Moslem
prisoners.
The main resolution would authorise 'all necessary means to ensure the
delivery of humanitarian assistance'. This implies use of force, but it does
not spell out exactly what would be involved or who would organise it.
The draft leaves open a number of options. It calls on all states to 'take
nationally or through regional agencies or arrangements all measures
necessary to facilitate, in co-ordination with the UN, the delivery by
relevant UN humanitarian organisations and others of humanitarian assistance
to Sarajevo and, wherever needed, in other parts of Bosnia-Hercegovina'.
This resolution also 'demands that unimpeded and continuous access to camps,
prisons and detention centres be granted immediately to the International
Committee of the Red Cross and other relevant humanitarian organisations and
that all detainees therein receive humane treatment, including adequate
food, shelter and medical care'.
Elaborating on western concern about reports of atrocities, the second
resolution repeats a demand for access to detention centres and expresses
'grave alarm' at reports of abuses against civilians.
In London, prime minister John Major's office confirmed that British ground
troops and airmen might be called on to protect the flow of relief to
victims of the fighting in Bosnia. Downing Street said Britain was
negotiating with the US and France to determine what each would contribute
to an escort force to protect aid convoys.
Officials added that the precise role and command structure of the escort
forces involved striking a delicate political balance to keep the UN on
board.
In Brussels, Nato started drawing up contingency plans to send troops to
Bosnia, but senior Nato officials and other military experts voiced concern
about the difficulties and dangers of committing forces to the region.
In London, Mr Willem Van Eekelen, secretary-general of the WEU, the
nine-nation European grouping, said international relief convoys should be
protected by European forces, but backed by US air-power.
There was a lull in fighting around the besieged Bosnian capital of Sarajevo
yesterday, but residents said they were running out of bread.
The Red Cross confirmed it received permission to visit detention camps in
Bosnia.
Further reports, Page 2
</TEXT>
