<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / Computer bug alert for 14m credit card accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster is alert-ing its credit card holders to problems it has
had with the com-puter system which processes 14m card accounts, more than
half of all of those in Britain.
The bank is also considering possible recourse against First Data Resources,
the operator of the computer system, for mistakes caused by the glitch. The
cards affected include those of Mastercard, Visa and Access offered by
NatWest, Midland, Lloyds, Royal Bank of Scotland and TSB, which are
processed through a computer centre with sites in Southend and Basildon.
At least several hundred people are thought to have had problems using their
cards because of a change in the computer software which took place in
mid-July. First Data Resources and the banks yesterday played down the
extent of the errors, which they said had been corrected.
NatWest's warning to its credit card holders comes in a letter which also
apologises for the problems. They include incorrect charges for late payment
and interest, delays in direct debits, fees for cash advances which did not
take place, incorrect amounts debited and incorrect transaction dates on
statements.
Several people have also reported that retailers have been unable to obtain
authorisation to accept their credit cards when there has been no apparent
reason why they should be refused.
Mr Gary Tobin, senior vice-president of communications and government
affairs at First Data Corporation, the parent of First Data Resources, said
there had been some 'fine-tuning' of the computer system between July 17 and
July 23 when the software was changed and tested.
But he said all the problems had been overcome, and that a few errors were
inevitable on a system processing so many accounts during an exercise
described by one of his colleagues as 'the biggest (computer software)
conversion in history'.
The change from the old system operated by Signet, a company which First
Data acquired last year, was designed to improve security, offer more
services and operate more quickly.
None of the banks would give full details on the number of customers
affected, although Lloyds Bank said it had written two weeks ago to 40 card
customers who had had more than their monthly payments directly debited from
their bank accounts.
