FT  11 AUG 92 / N-plant granted 10-year extension
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S oldest nuclear reactor, Bradwell, at Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, is to
continue running for another 10 years, Juliet Sychrava writes.
Friends of the Earth, the environmental pressure group, says the decision by
the Nuclear Installations Inspectorate to allow the Magnox-type reactor an
extended lease of life will put the lives of local people at risk.
The group said that radioactive discharges from Bradwell were outside the
new recommendations laid down by the Radiological Protection Board. Nuclear
Electric, the state-owned operator of the nuclear stations in England and
Wales, said it had satisfied the inspectorate that Bradwell presented no
danger. It said it was well within the legal limits and added that it was
looking at reductions in radioactivity.
Bradwell, which generates 245MW a year, or enough power to supply
Chelmsford, Colchester, and Southend, began generating electricity in July
1962.
