<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / Retirement for all at age 60 urged by TUC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STATE retirement age of 65 for both men and women could be twice as
expensive for the government as harmonising the age at 60, according to the
Trades Union Congress.
In a response to last week's recommendation by the Social Security Advisory
Committee of a pension age of 65, the TUC also says that equalising the age
at 60 is the most socially progressive option and takes account of social
trends and people's wishes.
The advisory committee had agreed with the government that raising the
retirement age of women from 60 to 65, the same as for men, would save
roughly Pounds 3bn a year in additional expenditure. However, the TUC says
in a letter to Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, that independent
calculations produced for it show that the 65 choice might cost Pounds
1.4bn. The cost of equalising the age at 60 might be Pounds 700m.
To arrive at the Pounds 700m cost for a retirement age of 60, the TUC has
assumed that economic activity rates for men aged between 60 and 65 will
eventually fall to 30 per cent from the present 53 per cent.
In arriving at the Pounds 1.4bn figure for equalising at 65, the TUC assumes
the proportion of women retiring after 60 would increase to about the same
as for men. It also assumes that about half of the jobs filled by women who
postpone retirement would otherwise have been available to job seekers.
Mr Norman Willis, TUC general secretary, says: 'On this basis, an increase
in the state pension age for women actually increases the net cost to the
economy as a whole.'
Mr Willis says that although it is not possible to say with any certainty
which figures are correct, 'the TUC's figures are certainly within the
bounds of possibility'.
</TEXT>
