<HEADLINE>
FT  11 AUG 92 / International Company News: Coca-Cola Amatil rises 19% in
first six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SUCCESSFUL international diversification has helped Coca-Cola Amatil,
Australia's biggest soft drink and snack food company, overcome recessed
domestic conditions and record a solid earnings rise in the first half to
June.
The company yesterday announced a 19 per cent advance in net profits to
ADollars 25.1m (USDollars 18.5m) from ADollars 21.1m a year earlier, on a 15
per cent rise in sales to ADollars 968.3m. from ADollars 841.7m. The interim
dividend is being raised to 8.5 cents a share from 7.5 cents.
A breakdown of pre-tax profits showed that profits from Australia fell to
ADollars 59.9m from ADollars 64.3m, on virtually static sales of ADollars
640.5m.
However, combined earnings of the company's Asian and European divisions
jumped to ADollars 26.5m from ADollars 16.4m on a 62 per cent jump in sales
from ADollars 200.1m to ADollars 324.8m.
The bulk of earnings again came from the company's beverage division, which
lifted pre-tax profits to ADollars 70.6m from ADollars 68.5m, while the
snack food division's profits rose to ADollars 15.7m from ADollars 12.3m.
The directors said soft drinks in Austria, Hungary and Czechoslovakia
continued to achieve growth in sales and profits, but European snack food
businesses were affected by intense competition.
West Australian Newspaper Holdings, the newly floated Perth media group, is
on the way to exceeding its prospectus forecasts for the current year to
June, after a solid maiden earnings report yesterday.
The group unveiled net profits of ADollars 14.1m for the six months to June
30, it's first period as a public company. Sales totalled ADollars 101.4m
and a 4 cents a share final dividend has been declared.
Mr Trevor Eastwood, chairman, said yesterday that transactions during the
period under review lifted the group's estimated tax losses to about
ADollars 320m from ADollars 79.9m, subject to tax office approval.
</TEXT>
