<DOCNO>FT923-8623</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CHMAPADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920810
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / US, Israel edge towards pact: Bush-Rabin meeting raises
hopes of progress in Mideast talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A distinct improvement in relations between the US and Israel will be marked
today when President George Bush and prime minister Yitzhak Rabin hold the
first of two meetings.
Although preparations for the talks, at Mr Bush's holiday home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, have been overshadowed by the crisis in
Bosnia-Hercegovina, the two leaders are expected to reach broad agreement on
the provision of US loan guarantees and on the next stage of Middle East
peace talks, scheduled to resume in Washington in two weeks.
Prospects for progress at the talks received a boost yesterday when Israel
proposed legalising contacts with the Palestine Liberation Organisation,
firmly viewed as a terrorist organisation by the government of former
premier Yitzhak Shamir.
Mr Bush and Mr James Baker, the secretary of state, made no secret of their
wish for Mr Rabin to lead the Labour party to victory in June's elections.
Under Mr Shamir, relations between Israel and the US had fallen to their
lowest level since the Israeli invasion of Lebanon and siege of Beirut in
1982.
Mr Shamir's refusal to contemplate relinquishing control over the Arab
territories occupied by Israel in 1967 in defiance of UN resolutions came to
be seen in the US as the main obstacle on the path towards a Middle East
peace agreement.
The US response to Mr Shamir's commitment to retain the territories was to
refuse the Dollars 10bn (Pounds 5.2bn) in loan guarantees Israel needed to
house Soviet immigrants, unless Israel first stopped building new
settlements in the West Bank and Gaza.
The refusal represented the most serious setback suffered by Israel in
Washington for many years and Mr Rabin has moved quickly to ban most new
settlement building in the occupied territories.
The loan guarantees, however, are unlikely to be provided without some
further debate.
Suggestions have been made that the US would like some offset arrangement
included which would allow American companies to take part in the building
programme.
Mr Rabin is also expected to outline to Mr Bush the proposals that Israeli
negotiators will put on the table when peace talks resume in Washington. He
is looking for agreement by early next year on some form of interim
Palestinian self-governing authority which would administer the territories
prior to an eventual conference to decide their final status.
With Mr Rabin keen to demonstrate early achievements in the face of
hostility from the right-wing and settlers' organisations at home and Mr
Bush trailing far behind Governor Bill Clinton in the US presidential
election race, both men have powerful reasons for wanting the talks to
succeed.
A successful resumption of Middle East peace negotiations might also allow
Mr Bush to deflect some of the political damage done to his Gulf war triumph
by the fresh challenges to UN ceasefire agreements being made by Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein.
Page 4
Israeli pledge to legalise PLO contact
Settlers and army back off from clash
</TEXT>
