<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Northern recovery held back by south
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY and EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE north-west of England and north Wales are experiencing tentative
improvements in economic activity but the depressed south-east is holding
back recovery. Those are the findings of regional surveys by chambers of
commerce in Manchester and Liverpool, and the latest Lloyds Bank Economic
Bulletin.
Prospects in the service sector in the north of England have been improving
for five successive quarters. Manchester chamber for the first time in two
years reported more service companies taking on labour than shedding it.
Low levels of spending in the still relative wealthy south-east, though, are
preventing a national recovery and restraining the investment plans of
northern companies.
In the Manchester chamber's region, manufacturers' investment intentions
moved into positive balance - more planning to increase investment than
decrease - but were still in negative balance and declining in Merseyside's
catchment area.
Mr Ian Berry, chief executive of Liverpool chamber, warned: 'Nearly half our
firms are still reducing investment in new plant and machinery. This will be
disastrous for future prosperity unless the trend is reversed.'
The north of England has suffered less than the south in the recession,
correcting much of the growth of inequality in income levels between the
regions.
Incomes per head in the south-east have fallen relative to the national
average to levels not seen for 10 years, said Mr Patrick Foley, Lloyds
Bank's chief economic adviser.
He said, however, that south-east incomes remain 15 per cent higher than the
national average, and the region is still best placed to lead Britain out of
recession. 'The south-east has the most confident consumers and has also
seen the largest adjustment in the overheated housing market. The region
seems set to lead the recovery when it happens.'
The northern surveys suggest that confidence is rising in all sectors except
the building industry. Manufacturers are struggling with a flat UK market,
but more are reporting rising export sales than a decline.
The chambers cover an area with more than 7m people from the Lake District
to mid Wales, accounting for more than 10 per cent of UK gross domestic
product. The surveys, of second-quarter trends, involved 930 companies
employing more than 150,000 people.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
