<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Paper hopes go through the shredder: How Continental 'green'
laws are hampering recycling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Williams, chief executive of David S. Smith, the company that
collects and recycles almost a quarter of the UK's waste paper, says he is
watching his industry 'go down the pan'.
In recent months he has campaigned vigorously to air his concerns about the
deteriorating competitiveness of the UK paper packaging industry. He argues
that the deterioration stems not from the recession but from environmental
legislation introduced by several countries in mainland Europe - most
notably Germany.
A glut of cheap waste paper across the Channel has enabled Continental
recycling companies to obtain their raw materials more cheaply than their
counterparts in the UK (see graph). That allows them significantly to
undercut David S. Smith's prices.
In a letter to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, in April,
Mr Williams urged the government to take action to address a situation of
'crisis proportions'.
He warned that the profitability of the industry had plunged, capacity was
being cut, and - in contrast to all other European countries - the UK's
paper recycling rate was actually falling.
If nothing is done, he predicts that the industry will shrink by up to 20
per cent by the end of the decade, with the balance of trade being Pounds
1bn to the worse. Moreover, the government's target of recycling 25 per cent
of all household waste by the year 2000 would be unattainable because of
lack of capacity, he told Mr Heseltine in a subsequent meeting.
Such talk may sound alarmist, but others echo his concerns. Mr Bryan
Bateman, director of business and the environment at the British Paper and
Board Industry Federation, the trade body, says: 'The problems affecting
this particular sector arise because of the singularities of the German
legislation and the differences in raw-material prices that the respective
countries now enjoy.
'Corresponding legislative thrusts in France and Holland have mitigated the
effects in their countries. But there is no desire or capability to have
similar legislation in the UK.'
Although other sectors of the packaging industry have felt ripples from the
stone that the Germans have thrown into the recycling pond, the UK paper
industry is particularly vulnerable because of its dependence on recycled
materials to sustain its competitiveness.
In the 1960s and 1970s, large parts of the UK paper industry were destroyed
by their general uncompetitiveness against the large-scale Nordic
manufacturers.
Then after extensive rationalisation and investment, the industry recovered
strongly through the 1980s and was greatly helped by tapping into a cheap
source of recycled materials from Britain's 'urban forests'.
Almost 60 per cent of the 5m tonnes of paper and board produced in the UK
each year now uses recycled paper - a far higher utilisation rate than in
almost every other industrialised country. But because the UK imports
another 4m tonnes of paper each year, its recycling rate as a proportion of
total consumption is only 33 per cent - one of the lowest in Europe.
Mr Bateman argues that the UK could realistically collect another 1m tonnes
of paper a year but that the recycling rate can be substantially increased
only by expanding manufacturing capacity. 'But that means increasing
investment which can only be funded by generating profitability in a stable
market,' he says.
One example of how difficult it can be to plan substantial investment
programmes is provided by SCA, the Swedish paper company, which is
contemplating investing about Pounds 250m in a newsprint mill, using
recycled paper, at Aylesford in Kent.
SCA's calculations are complicated by disagreements over proposed government
subsidies, a surge of imports of cheap Canadian newsprint manufactured from
virgin pulp - diverted from US markets because of state environmental
regulations stipulating set percentages for recycled materials in newspapers
 -and the prospect of four German newsprint mills due to start production
soon. They will soak up surplus local recycled paper.
Such investments would be aided if the UK were to follow the German route
and in effect force local authorities and industry to collect a greater
proportion of waste for re-use. That would have the effect of reducing
prices for raw materials, guaranteeing a reliable source of supply, enabling
investment decisions to be taken within a stable framework and allowing the
UK industry to compete on level terms with Continental competitors.
However, the UK government shows no signs of doing any such thing. It
harbours serious misgivings about the environmental impact of the German
system, arguing that more energy is consumed in collecting materials than is
recovered from recycling them. Ideologically it also prefers market-based
solutions to legislative or administrative ones. It is contemplating what
incentives it could introduce.
Some industry observers suggest that raising the costs of tipping recyclable
materials in landfill sites or imposing a levy on packaging products to
subsidise recycling schemes would have beneficial effects. Others propose
removing value added tax from recycled products to encourage greater
consumer demand - although it is unlikely that the Treasury would approve.
Whatever it decides, the government will have to act soon. A recent survey
by Friends of the Earth, the environmental pressure group, of 402
waste-collection authorities in England and Wales estimated that the
recycling rate for all household waste is just 4.4 per cent, up from 2.6 per
cent the year before, but below the government's estimates in the 1990
environment white paper.
The group commented that most local authorities would find it
near-impossible to achieve the government's suggested 25 per cent recycling
rate because of a lack of end markets for recycled materials. It urged the
government to tip the balance in favour of recycling by introducing a
national waste strategy.
Unless the government does so, Mr Williams is fearful for the future of the
recycling industry.
'The impact of the German environmental legislation has been to give the
German paper industry a significant cost/price advantage over the UK
industry through indirect subsidies,' he says. 'The situation is really
quite incredible. The German industry will move ahead while the British
industry will be devastated.'
</TEXT>
