<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Tory MPs warn on council tax valuations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSERVATIVE MPs and local authorities are concerned that valuations of
properties for the council tax, which will replace the poll tax, may provoke
resentment and a mass of appeals next year. This is because they are based
on two-year-old valuations, without any allowance for the decline in
property prices since then.
The concern is greatest in London, where the drop has been steepest. Sir
Rhodes Boyson, the Tory MP for Brent North and a former local-government
minister, warned yesterday that householders in London and the south-east
would feel 'betrayed' if their first council tax bill in April comes to
significantly more than their poll tax.
He urged the government to send civil servants to 'individual streets' to
compare next year's likely bill with what people are paying this year.
If people are going to be faced with larger bills, then the government 'may
again be walking off the cliff-end' as it did with the community charge, he
warned.
The timing of the change was also unfortunate, he said, coming during 'a
major recession' when 'people are battling to survive'. Because of the price
of property, the council tax would 'disadvantage seriously' those who live
in London and the south-east.
For council-tax purposes, properties are being allocated to one of eight
bands by their estimated value in April 1991. The tax payable will rise from
Pounds 361 a year for properties in the lowest band (properties valued up to
Pounds 40,000) to Pounds 1,078 for those in the top band (payable for
properties valued at more than Pounds 320,000).
Homeowners will have a right of appeal against the valuation of their
properties, but the Department of the Environment insists that appeals will
not be allowed on the basis of price falls since April 1991. Since
properties in London and the south-east, which will fall disproportionately
among the higher-value bands, have suffered the greatest losses in the past
two years, the number of aggrieved taxpayers is likely to be considerable.
Sir Rhodes urged the government either to introduce a separate set of bands
to take account of higher property values in London and the south-east, or
to put London properties in a band lower than that appropriate to their
value.
</TEXT>
