<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Councils 'fail to exploit' volunteers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities are failing to exploit volunteers as a resource in
developing their community care programmes, according to Community Service
Volunteers, a charity that organises voluntary effort.
A survey by the charity of half of all local authorities in England and
Wales found that in spite of rising demand for community carers, only 14 per
cent of councils had a clear strategy for recruiting and deploying
volunteers. Barely two thirds even consider volunteers. The charity noted
that although all authorities mention the voluntary sector in their plans,
many refer only to services bought in from professionals employed by
voluntary organisations.
The charity reports an increase of nearly a third in the number of young
people putting themselves forward under the organisation's full-time
volunteer scheme. A recent survey by the organisation showed that up to 50
per cent of older people would give time for organised voluntary work if
they were asked.
Ms Elisabeth Hoodless, director of the charity, said: 'Councils should
develop clear strategies for involving volunteers - a flexible,
cost-effective and highly motivated resource.'
