<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Private post operators may win local licences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is considering a plan to allow private postal operators to
bid for licences to compete with the Post Office in different regions. The
move is part of the government's review of the organisation of the Post
Office.
Ministers are not expected to make a decision until the end of the year and
the licences plan is the most radical under consideration.
The Post Office's letters division, Royal Mail, has a monopoly on delivering
all letters with postage costs of less than Pounds 1. Business Post, an
express delivery service company which submitted the proposal, would like to
offer a comprehensive letter service in part of the UK.
Because of the size of the Post Office - it made pre-tax profits of Pounds
247m for the year to March 29 this year - Business Post believes that
private operators should be given the opportunity to compete in different
parts of the UK. Under its plan, private operators would bid for the
franchise to compete exclusively with the Post Office in northern England,
for example. No private postal operator would set up a rival service in an
area where another private company was operating.
Mr Michael Kane, managing director of Business Post, said: 'No private
postal operator can compete effectively with the Post Office throughout the
UK. But there would be plenty of companies which could compete with the Post
Office in certain regional areas.'
He has already had talks with officials from the Department of Trade and
Industry and plans further meetings. He said: 'The DTI appear very keen on
our idea and are scheduled to come to our offices to see how it could work.'
The DTI says it is considering all proposals.
Business Post's plan also envisages the creation of an independent regulator
that would introduce competition progressively.
Mr Kane proposes the gradual introduction of competition along the same
lines as the telecommunications industry, where licences are issued for an
initial period to private operators who satisfy certain conditions.
He says he realises that the conditions would have to include compulsory
services to rural areas, but that would present no obstacle to those already
operating parcel-delivery services to such areas.
Since the Post Office cross-subsidises deliveries to these non-profitable
regions with the surplus from the profitable urban areas, Mr Kane says he
believes there is no reason why private operators should not be able to do
the same.
A sale that promises to pay on delivery, Page 13
</TEXT>
