<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Copyright fears for address database
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROYAL Mail is worried that draft legislation approved earlier this year
by the European Commission will strip its Postal Address File - the official
list of UK postcodes - of its copyright protection, David Owen writes.
Ironically, the draft directive is intended to provide protection for
producers of databases. It would outlaw unfair copying of the contents of
databases such as computerised address lists for 10 years.
But lists such as the file, which have been in existence for more than 10
years, would not benefit from this protection. Meanwhile, UK regulations -
which unusually already give copyright protection to the type of database
covered by the directive - would cease to apply.
The Royal Mail is concerned that adoption of the directive - part of a
growing body of agreed or draft EC legislation on intellectual property  -
would undermine Britain's position of having arguably the best protection
for databases among EC states.
It has been advised that the proposed legislation may actually put British
database owners in a worse position than their European counterparts because
of the strength of the laws on unfair competition that apply in other
countries.
In the year to March, the list generated some Pounds 2m of revenue for Royal
Mail, whose pre-tax profits rose to Pounds 266m. The organisation, which the
government is considering selling, handles 61m letters a day.
</TEXT>
