<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / London homes boost expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of homes to be provided by housing associations for London's
growing population of homeless, needy, disadvantaged and disabled is
expected to rise by a third in 1993-94, according to plans due to be
announced today by the Housing Corporation.
Increased spending by housing associations has provided one of the few
bright spots in an otherwise depressed UK housing scene. During the three
months to the end of April, associations in Britain started work on 7,600
homes - 55 per cent more than during the corresponding period last year.
Grants to associations have risen sharply, as part of government plans for
them to take over the local authorities' role as the main providers of
social housing.
There have been fears, however, that housing association budgets might be
restricted as the government seeks to exert greater control over rising
public expenditure generally.
A great deal of attention, therefore, is expected to be paid to minimum
spending targets for 1993-94 for London and the Home Counties. Those are due
to be announced today by the Housing Corporation, which administers
public-sector grants to housing associations.
The corporation is expected to set a provisional target of 12,000 new homes
for the region. That compares with a target of 9,000 in the current
financial year.
To cover the costs, the corporation is expected to announce that it will
invest a minimum of Pounds 635m, of which Pounds 463m will be spent in the
London boroughs.
Housing associations will be expected to raise additional finance from
private investors. About 20 per cent of the associations' funds in London
and the Home Counties comes from private investors, mostly from building
societies and the mortgage-lending arms of banks.
The majority of the new homes will go to homeless families. About 12 per
cent of funds will be set aside to support associations representing black
and other ethnic minorities. Black families are four times as likely to be
homeless as their white counterparts, according to the London boroughs.
Funds will also be set aside to help the elderly and disabled, as well as
for special schemes to assist people to buy their own homes under
shared-ownership arrangements.
The number of homes built by housing associations in Britain as a whole is
expected to rise from 27,000 to more than 40,000 during the 12 months to the
end of March next year.
The estimated cost of the homes is Pounds 8bn, of which Pounds 1.5bn is
expected to come from private investors.
</TEXT>
