<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Building societies' performance praised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHELTENHAM &amp; Gloucester, the sixth-largest building society by asset size,
kept its place last year as the industry's star performer in the UBS
Phillips &amp; Drew building society league table.
The report by the securities house says that in spite of wide variations in
their profitability last year, the top 20 UK building societies are still
performing well in the worst housing market recession since the Second World
War.
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester easily outperformed the rest of the industry on 10
out of 12 financial indicators selected for the report.
They included an extremely low cost base, with management expenses running
at only 26 per cent of its total income; a much higher than average return
on assets; and a rapid growth in its asset size.
The only two indicators on which the society was below the industry average
were measures of capital strength.
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester's main rival for the top place in the industry was
Leeds Permanent, the fifth-largest society, but Abbey National, the retail
bank that shed building society status three years ago, would rank in second
place if it were still a society. Halifax, the industry giant, came fifth,
an improvement of four places on 1990.
At the other end of the league table, Birmingham Midshires, the 13th-largest
society, and Town &amp; Country, the 19th-largest, which made a Pounds 43m
pre-tax loss last year before merging with Woolwich, got low marks for
almost everything except capital strength.
Other societies that performed badly in the league table this year were
Skipton, which dropped from second position to 17th, and Alliance &amp;
Leicester, the fourth-largest society, down by 11 places to 14th position.
Mr John Wriglesworth, of UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said he believed that in spite
of its low place in the league table, Birmingham Midshires was in excellent
shape for the future.
He ruled out any prospect at the moment of a top-20 building society getting
into such financial trouble as Town &amp; Country and needing to be rescued by a
larger society.
Mr Wriglesworth singled out National &amp; Provincial, the seventh-largest
society which two years ago was forced to abort its plans for a stock market
flotation, as the most improved society.
There are considerable differences in the degree to which large societies
have been affected by bad debt.
Derbyshire, the 20th society by size, emerged as the one with the fewest bad
debts. Chelsea, Alliance &amp; Leicester, Portman, Birmingham Midshires,
Skipton, and Nationwide have the worst bad-debt experience.
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester has much better than average bad debt and arrears
experience, although it has absorbed several smaller societies with high
levels of bad debt in their loan books.
Most top-20 societies shed estate agency branches last year. Halifax, the
largest society, cut its estate agency network by 50 branches and Nationwide
dropped 35 branches.
Only one society, Alliance &amp; Leicester, says it is still considering
following Abbey National with a stock market flotation.
Four other societies, Halifax, Nationwide, Leeds Permanent and National &amp;
Provincial, still retain merchant banks to advise them on whether to convert
to plc status.
