<HEADLINE>
FT  10 AUG 92 / Industry pay deals remain stuck above 4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRY pay settlements have remained above 4 per cent for three
consecutive quarters, suggesting that wage inflation remains a threat to UK
competitiveness.
Manufacturing wage settlements averaged 4.3 per cent in the second quarter
of 1992, according to the latest Confederation of British Industry pay
databank, unchanged from the final quarter of 1991.
The news comes a week after calls for a freeze on public sector wages from
some Tory MPs and a proposal from Mr Howard Davies, the CBI's new
director-general, that the government pay bill should not increase in cash
terms. Any rises in pay rates should be financed, he said, through
'improvements in efficiency or reductions in government activity'.
The CBI said the settlements data were evidence that pay behaviour had
settled into the non-inflationary patterns of Britain's European
competitors.
Separate CBI figures showed that settlements paid by service sector
companies have fallen to 4.3 per cent in the first half of 1992, from 7.1
per cent a year ago.
'If that pattern can be maintained into the upturn, the wage-price spiral
will be broken to the permanent benefit of UK competitiveness and jobs,'
said Mr Ronnie Gilbert, director of employment affairs at the CBI.
But economists expressed surprise that the fall in wage settlements had
ground to a halt.
'The behaviour of wage settlements has been mystifying,' said Mr John
Shepperd, economist at SG Warburg Securities. 'These figures suggest that
the adjustment within the European exchange rate mechanism has a long way to
go.'
Pay settlements had to fall to 3 per cent if UK exporters were to hold their
own in Europe, said Dr John Philpott, director of the Employment Policy
Institute, the employment think tank.
'We need to see considerably more progress if we are to be optimistic about
maintaining Britain's competitiveness when the recovery comes,' he said.
'The question is how much more pain we have to endure to get settlements
down to a competitive level, let alone to a level consistent with Mr Major's
target of zero inflation.'
Unemployment in July is expected to have risen by 25,000, the 27th
consecutive monthly increase following an unexpectedly low rise of 7,000 in
June.
The figures will be released on Thursday, with average earnings data
expected to show wage inflation still well above 6 per cent a year.
Further evidence that the government faces mounting pressure to restrict
public sector pay emerged yesterday as the 6.5 per cent pay increase
recommended for top policemen was attacked.
Two Tory MPs - Mr John Townend, chairman of the backbench finance committee,
and Sir John Wheeler, chairman of the Commons home affairs committee -
called for a smaller deal.
Northern recovery held back by south, Page 7
Business overdrafts fall, Page 7
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
